Oil Volatility Slips on Smallest Futures Move in Three Weeks

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-04-05T20:40:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-05/oil-volatility-slips-on-smallest-futures-move-in-three-weeks.html
Oil options volatility slipped as
the underlying futures fell by 13 cents, the smallest one-day
move in more than three weeks, on signs demand may drop in the
U.S. and  China , the largest crude-consuming countries.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
May, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 28 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York , down
from 30.4 percent yesterday.  Oil for May delivery settled at $108.34 a barrel on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange . It touched $108.78 a barrel yesterday,
the highest intraday price since Sept. 24, 2008.  Todayâ€™s move was the smallest since March 14, when oil rose
3 cents. Futures have risen 25 percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
June $140 calls with 1,763 lots changing hands. They slipped 2
cents to 19 cents a barrel. June $120 calls, the next-most
active contract, fell 25 cents to $1.17 a barrel with 1,323
contracts trading. One contract is for 1,000 barrels of oil.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  June $125 calls were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 9,344 lots changing hands. They slid 7 cents to
84 cents a barrel. The next most active option, May $125 calls,
dropped 6 cents to 7 cents a barrel on 6,152 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $150 calls with 39,372
contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 38,942 and
December $120 calls with 38,713.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 